LFwp26AdY-SndDnvVp9QgUI0d2psj6huxqGXtHVWV6gdvP6kFdXRy3yseTw_q5JIWBRUzBh1Am7Z4uGVRd7A_yt5tzMPGD15gf2f4Oimx70kNhbv6h_rgJ1Q70CJWCdtpzUuy-5INDliVktKVBmdKduG2d7nr5QuNlnpk2OgM6lcwFEydd7QSss6tiYBJVSgNU4E4-VlDH9r1-gqmXNwOv8zy1r4UVwrEh9Qx_sp6HrWZkpp97xFWQagBZkFNkIEDF4QGY_-Wp1ltRmIOOrJrf_eLM-I0i-FfBpgdHnNNSL5M2zBi1U5iM3iPmxSMB7W7a9CzkdloKuev09uI_GLxbCR77Nh9zDy8zY3hOHMMnOhadBAV6YIi4sEgLjU2m5OrsjqB014BaSnaO3jGDUJoIt1IkeImeGyZDI5JHhP-qr4TCWM8PpF0Om-7FPBkJFs1qe-EGVpHMePr3_P9WZnySYRRbsWxY3o3eAKiPgP1CH40LpXATGBslDQAnfWACKQ91LiARv0f97F6AC2dHhhnOFJ5wrkWC-7vAxzM6Ry0u2_PorQFb0nvWENuu7eEPx7lMKhGAh46-aFvzjXlwX-DjHQ4EU8DeMicQno0BHsQYnEb-PpRpfUQDocoem2Ej_xNvEIHegg1PqC4Bjj98HLsOWVPI2cfn2jLXGa9zwGHmCdWJmvY5nCfnFImCUd-j5dA8ttC3SsT_NfTZ2yxO_yOZW_X94NaOO8jLnL27lTjE84NLHMYyOQkE88pOzdG5mZwz6LrBGdDslmgThG0kw_kfqfU6kEGJukYZNs_C_iPrdUIv7NALmBJxnVesm90-es3SunDBsLKb4p9joSEnkOimVchqUMPO7cGwmlzu3gtaj_rR15--Qua5xH-EhKvEt2yN1ed3xchDHwICgibkdgZ3dfLAiu-mRq4187BcmLO_wCl-6kk8\",\"summary\":[{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering test coverage**\\n\\nI’m thinking about whether we need robust coverage since the `get` instance method of `Field` requires the initialization of `FactoryFinder`. If `FactoryFinder` was previously initialized in another test, there might be sufficient coverage already. But I wonder if running tests after using a factory finder could impact the results. I need to ensure that the class isn't initialized during the native image build, as that might affect dynamic access coverage. This is a nuanced situation, and I'm still figuring it out!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Analyzing FactoryFinder behavior**\\n\\nI’m trying to determine the relevance of native tests for `FactoryFinder`. The static initialization of `FACTORIES_CACHE` creates a potential runtime problem with `CurrentThreadToServletContext`. If I only import the static final constant, that could change things. I wonder if we should implement a cleanup function for factory release, but maybe it isn't necessary. However, there's a risk that existing logging may affect future tests due to the special initialization detection. It feels complicated, and I’m still figuring out the best approach!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering FactoryFinder effects**\\n\\nI’m thinking about the potential impacts of `FactoryFinder`, especially when the current context is non-null, which could lead to issues later. It seems there’s no public reset option except for the release, which only resets under specific conditions. Maybe I could create a non-null `FacesContext` before the release to avoid side effects, but that feels complicated. Alternatively, using a separate thread could help, although managing the logging flags on the static cache could get tricky. Lots to consider here!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating test logic and thread usage**\\n\\nI need to check the maximum line length, probably around 160 characters, which seems reasonable. I’m wondering if I should generate a count of tests. But does the call to FacesContext.getCurrentInstance affect this if there's already a current instance on the same thread? JUnit often reuses the same thread, but tests do close. To be safe, I could use a new thread without any active ThreadLocal. Though, would the Field#get class initialization happen in the new thread? If the factory isn't initialized, it creates a tricky situation.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Refining test logic for independence**\\n\\nI’m contemplating whether we really need this step. Active call sites are in the constructor, and if this test's assertion detects a non-null current instance from leftovers, it means FactoryFinder might not be called, which could lead to assertion failures. If there’s no assertion? Well, we can’t just ignore null checks. To make this test meaningful, I think using a new thread can help. It might be better to run it in a single-threaded executor, set the TCCL, and call it that way. That should eliminate any ThreadLocal concerns.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Clarifying threading approach**\\n\\nI'm considering the threading situation, figuring out that creating a new thread is tricky due to the current context. It seems like the class loader might return some context, but my factory map is empty. That's a relief, but I need to ensure I close the executor properly. A straightforward thread with a join could work, but I should definitely handle exceptions. Using ExecutorService is more idiomatic, so I’ll add a Future and test it with a timeout under 60 seconds. Time to edit!\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_wAjVE4az1iW49Sl3AZOIuUlc|fc_01c5c6bbe2b8f4d9016a01f3b922c48192b4a20d62f99e1e39", "name": "edit", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/jakarta.platform/jakarta.jakartaee-api/10.0.0/src/test/java/jakarta_platform/jakarta_jakartaee_api/ServletContextFacesContextFactoryTest.java", "edits": [{"oldText": "import jakarta.faces.context.FacesContext;\n\nimport org.junit.jupiter.api.Test;\n\npublic class ServletContextFacesContextFactoryTest {\n    @Test\n    void currentInstanceUsesServletContextAwareFactoryLookupWhenNoFacesContextIsActive() {\n        ClassLoader previousContextClassLoader = Thread.currentThread().getContextClassLoader();\n\n        try {\n            Thread.currentThread().setContextClassLoader(ServletContextFacesContextFactoryTest.class.getClassLoader());\n\n            FacesContext currentInstance = FacesContext.getCurrentInstance();\n\n            assertThat(currentInstance).isNull();\n        } finally {\n            Thread.currentThread().setContextClassLoader(previousContextClassLoader);\n        }\n    }\n}\n", "newText": "import java.util.concurrent.ExecutorService;\nimport java.util.concurrent.Executors;\nimport java.util.concurrent.Future;\nimport java.util.concurrent.TimeUnit;\n\nimport jakarta.faces.context.FacesContext;\n\nimport org.junit.jupiter.api.Test;\n\npublic class ServletContextFacesContextFactoryTest {\n    @Test\n    void currentInstanceUsesServletContextAwareFactoryLookupWhenNoFacesContextIsActive() throws Exception {\n        ExecutorService executor = Executors.newSingleThreadExecutor();\n        try {\n            Future<FacesContext> currentInstance = executor.submit(() -> {\n                Thread.currentThread().setContextClassLoader(ServletContextFacesContextFactoryTest.class.getClassLoader());\n                return FacesContext.getCurrentInstance();\n            });\n\n            assertThat(currentInstance.get(10, TimeUnit.SECONDS)).isNull();\n        } finally {\n            executor.shutdownNow();\n            assertThat(executor.awaitTermination(10, TimeUnit.SECONDS)).isTrue();\n        }\n    }\n}\n"}]}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 1297, "output": 1537, "cacheRead": 32768, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 35602, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1778512801447, "responseId": "resp_01c5c6bbe2b8f4d9016a01f3a217188192810ec087c46698ad"}}
[tool-exec] start id=call_wAjVE4az1iW49Sl3AZOIuUlc|fc_01c5c6bbe2b8f4d9016a01f3b922c48192b4a20d62f99e1e39 name=edit args={"path": "tests/src/jakarta.platform/jakarta.jakartaee-api/10.0.0/src/test/java/jakarta_platform/jakarta_jakartaee_api/ServletContextFacesContextFactoryTest.java", "edits": [{"oldText": "import jakarta.faces.context.FacesContext;\n\nimport org.junit.jupiter.api.Test;\n\npublic class ServletContextFacesContextFactoryTest {\n    @Test\n    void currentInstanceUsesServletContextAwareFactoryLookupWhenNoFacesContextIsActive() {\n        ClassLoader previousContextClassLoader = Thread.currentThread().getContextClassLoader();\n\n        try {\n            Thread.currentThread().setContextClassLoader(ServletContextFacesContextFactoryTest.class.getClassLoader());\n\n            FacesContext currentInstance = FacesContext.getCurrentInstance();\n\n            assertThat(currentInstance).isNull();\n        } finally {\n            Thread.currentThread().setContextClassLoader(previousContextClassLoader);\n        }\n    }\n}\n", "newText": "import java.util.concurrent.ExecutorService;\nimport java.util.concurrent.Executors;\nimport java.util.concurrent.Future;\nimport java.util.concurrent.TimeUnit;\n\nimport jakarta.faces.context.FacesContext;\n\nimport org.junit.jupiter.api.Test;\n\npublic class ServletContextFacesContextFactoryTest {\n    @Test\n    void currentInstanceUsesServletContextAwareFactoryLookupWhenNoFacesContextIsActive() throws Exception {\n        ExecutorService executor = Executors.newSingleThreadExecutor();\n        try {\n            Future<FacesContext> currentInstance = executor.submit(() -> {\n                Thread.currentThread().setContextClassLoader(ServletContextFacesContextFactoryTest.class.getClassLoader());\n                return FacesContext.getCurrentInstance();\n            });\n\n            assertThat(currentInstance.get(10, TimeUnit.SECONDS)).isNull();\n        } finally {\n            executor.shutdownNow();\n            assertThat(executor.awaitTermination(10, TimeUnit.SECONDS)).isTrue();\n        }\n    }\n}\n"}]}
